# Kardano SDK — Phase 0 Guardrails

Full details in `docs/AI_WORKING_AGREEMENT.md`. UI-free Kotlin Multiplatform Cardano SDK
(Android/iOS/JVM), group `org.sarmidev.kardano`.

## Hard rules (never violate)

- No handwritten cryptographic algorithms (Blake2b, Ed25519, SHA, etc.).
- No transaction signing.
- No real mnemonics, private keys, or anything touching real funds — anywhere.
- No banned words: `secure`, `safe`, `hardened`, `audited`, `production-ready`,
  `guaranteed`, `cryptographically safe`. Use factual wording instead.
- Keep the SDK core UI-free and lean; no dependency without a documented rationale.
- Do not modify Gradle, Kotlin source, iOS, or Android project files unless the task
  explicitly authorizes it.
- No dynamic (`+`) or unpinned dependency versions.

## Phase 0 scope

Byte primitives, hex, Bech32/Bech32m, a minimal documented CBOR subset, and structural
CIP-19 address validation (parsing only). Crypto is `expect`/strategy docs only.
Before implementing CBOR or Bech32, check `docs/DECISIONS/0001-cbor-and-parser-policy.md`.

## Parser safety (applies to CBOR, Bech32, hex, address)

- Never allocate a buffer from an untrusted length field.
- Enforce named constants: `MAX_INPUT_BYTES`, `MAX_NESTING_DEPTH`, `MAX_COLLECTION_ELEMENTS`.
- Reject malformed, non-canonical, or unsupported input — never normalize it.
- Reject out-of-range numeric values; never truncate silently.

## KMP error policy

- Public APIs that can fail return a sealed error or `Result` type — no throwing.
- Any unavoidable thrower must have `@Throws` and be documented in KDoc.
- Throwing across the Swift/ObjC boundary crashes iOS.

## ByteArray correctness

- Use `contentEquals` / `contentHashCode` — never `ByteArray ==`.
- Defensive copy on construction and accessors.
- Never expose a mutable internal `ByteArray`.

## Test integrity

- Never invent test vectors — copy them verbatim from cited specs.
- Never weaken a validator to make a test pass.
- `decode(encode(x)) == x` is safe. `encode(decode(y)) == y` must not silently accept
  non-canonical input — if tested, also assert non-canonical input is rejected.

## Working style

- One logical change per diff; target < ~300–400 changed lines.
- Broad refactors require a short written plan before editing.
- A change is not done until tests and docs are updated.

## Definition of done

- Compiles: common, JVM, Android (where applicable), iOS simulator (where applicable).
- Tests pass; new behavior has valid/invalid/edge tests.
- Security-sensitive behavior cites external test vectors (BIP-173/350, RFC 8949, CIP-19).
- Public APIs have KDoc; validators say "structural only" where applicable.
- Docs updated in the same change.
- No banned words or unsafe claims.
- Diff is manually reviewable.
